          "id": "human-resource-management-401-l06-c1",
          "title": "The Gig Economy and Contingent Workforce",
          "content": "The gig economy is a modern way of working where individuals take on short-term jobs or projects instead of committing to a traditional full-time position. This includes various types of workers such as independent contractors, freelancers, temporary employees, and those who find work through online platforms like Uber, Upwork, and Fiverr. Recent studies show that approximately 36% of workers in the United States are engaged in gig work in some form. For businesses, hiring these contingent workers can bring numerous benefits. It allows for greater flexibility in staffing, provides access to specialized skills that may not be available in-house, and can lead to significant cost savings since these workers typically do not require benefits or long-term commitments. However, managing a workforce that includes both permanent and contingent workers can be challenging for Human Resources (HR) departments. One major issue is correctly classifying workers as either employees or independent contractors, as errors in this classification can result in serious legal penalties. Additionally, HR teams must develop strategies to engage non-permanent workers effectively, ensure that valuable knowledge is retained when contractors leave, and create a cohesive culture that includes all types of employees. It is also essential to guarantee that all workers, regardless of their employment status, are treated fairly and equitably. To successfully integrate permanent employees with contingent talent, organizations must establish new HR policies and management approaches that specifically address these unique challenges and foster a collaborative work environment.\nContext recap: The gig economy is a modern way of working where individuals take on short-term jobs or projects instead of committing to a traditional full-time position. This includes various types of workers such as independent contractors, freelancers, temporary employees, and those who find work through online platforms like Uber, Upwork, and Fiverr. Recent studies show that approximately 36% of workers in the United States are engaged in gig work in some form. For businesses, hiring these contingent workers can bring numerous benefits.\nWhy this matters: The Gig Economy and Contingent Workforce helps learners in Business connect ideas from Strategic HR & Future of Work to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
